{{Infobox court case |name = Commonwealth v. Twitchell |court = [[Supreme Judicial Court of Massachusetts]] |image = |imagesize = 160px |imagelink = |imagealt = |caption = |full name = Commonwealth v. David R. Twitchell; Commonwealth v. Ginger Twitchell |date decided = {{start date|1993|08|11|df=}} |citations = [https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/2040533/commonwealth-v-twitchell/ 416 Mass. 114]; 617 [[N.E.2d]] 609 |ECLI = |transcripts = |judges = [[Paul J. Liacos]], [[Herbert P. Wilkins]], [[Ruth Abrams]], [[Joseph R. Nolan]], [[Neil L. Lynch]], [[Francis Patrick O'Connor]], [[John M. Greaney]] |number of judges = |decision by = Wilkins |dissenting = Nolan |prior actions = |appealed from = |appealed to = |subsequent actions = |related actions = |opinions = |keywords = <!-- {{hlist | }} --> |italic title = yes }} '''''Commonwealth v. Twitchell''''', 416 Mass. 114, 617 N.E.2d 609 (1993),<ref name=Opinion>''Commonwealth v. Twitchell'', [https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/2040533/commonwealth-v-twitchell/ 416 Mass. 114, 617 N.E.2d 609] (1993).</ref> was the most prominent of a series of criminal cases, in the late 1980s and early 1990s, in which parents who were members of the [[Church of Christ, Scientist|Christian Science church]] were prosecuted for the deaths of children whose medical conditions had been treated only by Christian Science prayer.
In 1988, [[Massachusetts]] prosecutors charged David and Ginger Twitchell with [[manslaughter]] in the 1986 death of their two-year-old son Robyn. Robyn Twitchell died of a [[peritonitis]] caused by a bowel obstruction that medical professionals declared would have been easily correctable.
The Twitchells' defense contended that the couple were within their [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] rights to treat their son's illness with prayer and that Massachusetts had recognized this right in an exemption to the statute outlawing [[child neglect]].
The Twitchells were convicted of [[involuntary manslaughter]]. They were sentenced to ten years [[probation]] and required to bring their remaining children to regular visits to a [[pediatrician]].<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CE0D61030F935A3575BC0A966958260] ''New York Times'', 6 August 1990, In Child Deaths, a Test for Christian Science</ref><ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,970633-1,00.html] TIME, 16 July 1990, Convicted Of Relying on Prayer</ref> The conviction was overturned in 1993 by the [[Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court]] on a legal technicality.<ref name=Opinion/> Robert Gittens, speaking for the prosecutors' office commented, "the law is now clear: parents cannot sacrifice the lives of their children in the name of religious freedom."<ref>{{cite web| agency= Associated Press |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-08-12/news/mn-23106_1_christian-science|title=Court Overturns Conviction of Christian Science Couple |work=Los Angeles Times |date=1993-08-12 |accessdate=2013-01-19}}</ref>
