{{Short description|Hysiae was an Argive garrison town in Ancient Greece}}
'''Hysiae''' or '''Hysiai''' ({{lang-grc|Ὑσιαί}}), also '''Hysia''' (Ὑσία), was a garrison town of [[ancient Argolis]], also called the [[Argeia (region)|Argeia]], southern [[Greece]] during the [[Archaic Greece|archaic period]]. It was located to the southwest of [[Argos]] and east of [[Tegea]], on the road between them, at the foot of [[Mount Parthenium]], not far from the Argive border with [[ancient Laconia|Laconia]].<ref>{{Cite Pausanias|2|24|7}}, 8.6.4, 8.54.7.</ref><ref>{{Cite Strabo|viii. p.376}}</ref> In {{circa|669&nbsp;BCE}}, the [[Battle of Hysiae (c.669 BC)|First Battle of Hysiae]] was fought between the [[ancient Sparta|Spartans]] and the Argives, who won to repulse a Spartan invasion of Argolis.<ref>{{harvnb | Bury | Meiggs | 1975 | p=524}}</ref><ref>{{Cite Pausanias|2|24|7}}</ref> It appears to have been destroyed by the Argives, along with [[Tiryns]], [[Mycenae]], and the other towns in the Argeia, after the [[Greco-Persian Wars]];<ref>{{Cite Pausanias|8|27|1}}</ref> but it was afterwards restored, and was occupied by the Argives in the [[Peloponnesian War]] as a frontier-fortress. During the Peloponnesian War, in 417&nbsp;BCE, the [[Battle of Hysiae (417 BC)|Second Battle of Hysiae]] was fought, again between the Spartans and the Argives, and resulted in a decisive Spartan victory. The Spartans captured Hysiae and destroyed it; all captured male citizens were executed.<ref name="ThucV83">{{harvnb | Thucydides, v.83 | Warner | 1954 | p=399}}</ref><ref>{{Cite Thucydides|5.83}}</ref><ref>{{Cite Diodorus|12.81}}</ref>

Its site is located near modern [[Akhladokampos]].<ref>{{Cite Barrington|58}}</ref><ref>{{Cite DARE|21916}}</ref>

